Subject: Street Sweeping  at 11355 N Torrey Pines Rd, San Diego, CA 92121, USA
Public Description: There are some broken glass fragments in the bike lane of the southbound stretch of N. Torrey Pines Road approximately 500 yards south of the traffic signal at the top of the hill by National University.  These fragments could lead to flat tires and accidents to bicycle riders.  Therefore, street sweeping of the bike lane of the southbound N. Torrey Pines Road would enhance the safety of the many cyclists who ride on this road.  In addition, the northbound stretch of N. Torrey Pines Road from National University to the beach has three areas of broken glass on the side of the road.  The glass fragments are on the right side of the bike lane on the downhill grade.  These fragments appeared during the Del Mar Fair and are probably due to broken beer bottles etc.  The glass fragments are potentially dangerous to cyclists.  In summary, street sweeping of the bike lanes of both the northbound and southbound N. Torrey Pines Road in the grade from the beach to National University at the top of the hill would likely prevent accidents.

Subject: Storm Drain Grate frame broken or missing at 3762 El Cajon Blvd, San Diego, CA 92105, USA
Public Description: I was driving along El Cajon Blvd. at approximately 3:30PM on Friday, July 29, 2016, when at the intersection of El Cajon and McClintock St., I collided with an open service grate that was not marked by signs or cones. My view had been blocked by the car in front of me, and by the time it swerved and I saw the grate, it was too late to make an evasive action. The grate blew out my left front tire and severely damaged (but did not puncture) my left rear tire. My left front wheel was also damaged heavily. Luckily, I was able to stop at AM Mufflers & Tire just down the road to have a spare put on. The employee also gave me an estimate of the cost of two new tires and a new wheel, which I will be filing a claim for. Attached hereto are images of the damages to my car as well as the open maintenance grate I ran over. I walked along the median in order to take pictures with permission of a passing officer, who encouraged me to take these photos. This is surely a massive safety/damage hazard, and should be dealt with as soon as possible.

You can see the situation somewhat by using google street view, but to get an accurate sense, I recommend driving north down the alley from Indian to Joplin.

Subject: Street Sweeping  at 4770 Kane Street, San Diego, CA, United States
Public Description: I live at the intersection of Kane and Illion. The Sweeper comes down Illion, makes a U-turn and heads back up Illion. When the Sweeper makes its turn it invariably deposits a load of dirt and debris in the intersection, then continues on. I clean up the mess with a shovel, a broom and a bucket to carry the dirt.    It would be better if the Sweeper either did not come down Illion, or did not make a a U-turn at Kane and Illion. I took a video of the Sweeper this morning, and the debris it left on both Illion and in the intersection after I tried to talk to the driver. The driver refused to give me his name, would not open the window to the Sweeper so I could hear what he said, or so he could have heard what I said. He was a Philipino, about 32 years of age. His Sweeper number was 718-072. It was a Global Sweeper.The Sweeper drove off, then about five minutes later came back and cleaned up the mess which had been left behind. This is the FIRST and ONLY time the Sweeper has ever cleaned up the mess at the intersection. I assume it was because I complained to the driver, and after he left the first time he called someone who ordered him to go back and clean up his mess.Anthony Mournian4770 Kane StreetSan Diego, CA 92110 cell: 619-888-0886

Thank you.

Subject: Sidewalk  at 5455 Waverly Avenue, La Jolla, CA, United States
Public Description: There is a depression above the sewer trench between the sidewalk and curb in front of my elderly mother's home at 5455 Waverly Avenue.  The depression occurred after the City had a contractor make sewer line improvements to the sewer system during which they had excavated the sewer line, made the improvements, and then backfilled the trench and restored the brick pavement.  The soil in the trench backfill has settled (I am a certified engineering geologist and knowledge about this issue) and created a tripping hazard for my elderly mother.  I would like the city to remove the brick work and re-compact the trench backfill to make it level and prevent additional settlement from occurring, and then restore the brick work to remove the depression and tripping hazard.  I have request this be done through the City sewer department but I do not know if they will resolve the problem.  The parking strip between the curb and sidewalk is the City property and the work that caused the settlement was done by a City contractor for the City - therefore the City should repair the problem before my mother (or anyone else) stumbles over the depression and hurts themselves - possibly severely (which could happen to my elderly mother).  It would be much more cost effective for the City to fix this problem before anyone gets hurt rather than have to deal with a potential lawsuit if someone gets hurt.  Can you please respond to my request?Thank you,Kevin RogersProfessional Engineering Geologist and CitizenCEG 2425

Subject: Tree Hazard  at 4493 Idaho St, San Diego, CA 92116, United States
Public Description: 6/7/16  The seeds on this city property King Palm have the sidewalk full of seeds that are like marbles.  It's across from a kindergarden (Garfield Elementary) where their kids love running and rolling on your many marbles.  Many of them end up falling, but luckily none of them have yet been hurt (as far as we know).  I sweep it twice a week, but it's full of seeds within 2 days.  The huge dead branch's with their 12 inch thorns are falling too!  I was told that my copy of this notice releases me of any responsibility for any future possible injuries.  We are many times gone for weeks and come back to your piles of marbles in the street and sidewalk with a few of your deadly branches included.  Should I post this notice on the tree to inform any victims of where to call for injuries?  I'll keep sweeping and my many neighbors can back me up on that statement, but they'll also be able to mention the kindergardeners rolling on the many that keep falling a day or two later.  Luckily no kid or passer-by has yet been speared by one of those many falling branches.  Check it out ASAP!  Jeff Curtis. 619-280-1196 ( PS - If they do happen to trim it, it would be best if they trim the branches to an upward 45% angle with all of the seed pods included.  I used to trim palms many  years ago. A chainsaw is usually used for king palm trimmings).

It gives our neighborhood a "trashy" look, and tenants complain about this.  Please see that it is cleaned ASAP. Also, sediment from the hillside collects at the curb where the street sweeper NEVER cleans and thus the sediment is being blown into the storm drain there on a daily basis.  The City should erect a retaining wall at the bottom of the hillside to control the ongoing soil erosion into the street. If the City cannot see to it that this drain is cleaned promptly, I will send a complaint to the San Diego Regional Water Quality Control Board.

Subject: Storm Drain Clogged Storm Drain at 2255 Meadow Lark Dr, San Diego, CA 92123, USA
Public Description: CMP storm drain from Meadow Lark Dr. to channel at Mission Center Rd. needs to be repaired. It is failing and leaks water out at more than on spot on the hillside. As you can see in the picture it is adjacent to two high voltage transmission structures. The soil type on the hillside is a cobble and when any concentrated amount of water hits the hillside it easily erodes. We don't want to have a tower failure at this site due to the storm drain. It was patched in one area several years ago and the blockage at the bottom was cleared. However, it is leaking in other places uphill from the patch. we have installed BMPs to protect the towers but those are only temporary until the storm drain can be properly repaired. Due to the steepness and soil conditions this might be a prime candidate for relining. I must reiterate, there are four transmission circuits of critical importance to keeping the power on in San Diego. There are two 230kV, one 138kV and one 69kV on those two towers.

Subject: Traffic Sign  at Broadway and 26th-blocking stop sign
Public Description: I'm a resident at 924 26th Street. From my window, I see roughly 4 cars a day, who miss the stop sign at the intersection of 26th and Broadway. Almost without exception, those who speed through the intersection are traveling west on Broadway, toward downtown. In most cases, drivers miss the stop sign around 5pm to 7pm, when the setting sun shines directly in driver's eyes as they approach the intersection. The main problem, I believe, is that the stop sign is not clearly visible as you approach the intersection. The signs are hidden by tree branches and parked cars. The situation needs to be addressed before a child is hit and killed.

Subject: Storm Drain Channel Cleaning at 5135 University Avenue, San Diego, CA 92105, United States
Public Description: A)  The storm drain channel south of 5135 University Avenue is clogged by overgrown brush and trees growing inside the channel, including invasive species such as palm trees.  There is trash and litter in the channel at 5135 University Avenue and west of there, behind 5069 University Avenue, including a City sign that was left behind on January 6 when Storm Drain cleared a build up of branches and twigs from the upstream culvert entrances. Due to the successful growth of trees and shrubs planted in this location in 2007 when the 5135 Auburn Park low income housing complex was built, there is now an ongoing vegetative debris problem with this channel, whereas prior to the growth of tall trees and shrubs, this problem was likely minimal.  Therefore, per the recommendations found in the City's Storm Drain Maintenance Manual, a debris catch fence should be installed upstream from the two concrete culverts located behind 5069 University Avenue.  Because such a debris catch fence was lacking on January 5, 2016, tree debris accumulated across the upstream entrance to the two concrete culverts, preventing storm water from entering the culverts and thus the diversion of the water to properties to the south, including Wightman Street Neighborhood Park where massive flooding occurred.  Debris once again accumulated in May of 2016--I contacted Storm Drain to remove that debris and it did so.  However, debris build up will continue to occur in this area due to the current presence of now mature native trees and shrubs and the resultant year round dropping of twigs, and larger branches into the channel.    According to the records I found online, this portion of the channel was assessed in November 2015, but was NOT cleaned in December 2015 when other portions of the channel downstream from the culverts were cleaned.  The cleaning that was done during that time period began half way through the culverts, according to the report.  Thus this portion of the channel is overdue for: 1) brush removal, 2) litter removal, 3) restoration of original channel depth and width, and 4)  installation of a debris catch fence upstream from the two culverts to prevent future debris from clogging the culvert entrances and causing diversion of storm water to Wightman Street Neighborhood Park and other properties south of the channel.B) On the south side of the channel just ahead of the culvert entrances, a huge slab of the concrete lining the channel broke and slid down, exposing a swath of earth on the south side of the channel (where there is supposed to be concrete) and this will now erode and endanger the remaining concrete lining along the channel.C) There is graffiti everywhere.  There must be ongoing inspection and removal of such graffiti.D) Three difference homeless people have taken up residence in the culverts in succession over the last three months.  They were reported to Storm Drain employee, John Scampone, and were removed.  However, Storm Drain should clearly post No Trespassing signs on the culverts and also provide a hotline phone number for park goers to report transients from living in the culverts.  The defecation and urination that accompanies human habitation of the storm channel culverts and environs is a serious public health issue--and these two culverts connect to Wightman Street Neighborhood Park which is only 120 feet downstream from the culvert entrances.  If you have any questions please call me at 619-442-3821

Public Description: I?m a native San Diegan and one of the worst intersections is at Torrey Pines Rd and La Jolla Village Drive when heading west.As you  may know getting into downtown La Jolla when driving from 5 South is a meandering path. One must turn right on La Jolla Village Dr. Then Left on Torrey Pines Road. For a local, we know how to manage it. For those who don?t drive it regularly it is almost certain there will be at least one driver completely unaware of the important left turn on Torrey Pines Rd to get into La Jolla. Every time I drive to this intersection a dangerous series of events occur. Either from the far right lane or the middle lane a car insists on getting into the Left turn lane stopping traffic abruptly.Remedies:1) The best remedy is to create a La Jolla Parkway offramp for those driving down 5 South wanting to get to downtown La Jolla.2) Creating a type of barricade dividing the 2 lanes of La Jolla Village Drive towards UCSD after you pass the Villa La Jolla Drive intersection with signage ?to downtown La Jolla?. This signage could hang from the pedestrian bridge, or from the signal poll.3) Simply better signage before and at the intersection. LARGE signage: To downtown La Jolla LEFT lane. Right now the signage is not effective, it is small and on the far right noting a turn on the left. This signage could hang from the pedestrian bridge, or from the signal poll.

Subject: Street Light Light Out at 706 Stafford Pl, San Diego, CA 92107, USA
Public Description: The timeline  regarding the present lack of street lighting is as follows:There were two streetlights on the cul-de-sac when I moved into my house in 1994. One at the extreme southeast end of the cul-de-sac at a then existing driveway entrance and a second one in the parkway directly across from my home. Sometime after 2003 when my neighbor, Craig Irving, bought the three undeveloped parcels across from me to build a single family residence on the now combined property (4095 Lomaland Drive) both street lights were removed during construction since his improvements included the under grounding of the existing power lines. No replacement street lighting was installed after the removal of power poles. During the last few years since entry into the adjacent nature park was made accessible we have had a significant increase in traffic which unfortunately includes much illegal night time activity including, but certainly not limited to, over night camping, public urination and defecation, under age drinking, drug use, fornication and daily litter related to all of the above. It presents an unsafe condition for both my family and the young families that have recently moved into the immediate neighborhood. I am requesting that an individual light post be reinstalled at the previous location directly across from my home in the interest of discouraging the illegal behavior we have had to tolerate for far too long. Thank you for your attention to this matter, Tom Hayes

Subject: Tree Hazard  at 4493 Idaho St, San Diego, CA, United States
Public Description: I sent in a notice a couple of days ago about our king palm that is dropping its 20 ft. branches and the thousands of seeds every day.  Today I was walking north on Idaho St. and noticed a few more king palms with their huge branches in the street, and one of which has a shattered window glass all around it in the street.  I'm a corner house next to a elementary school where the kids love to run and roll on these seeds and fall half of the time, while others who are just crossing the street are unwantedly slipping and getting your seeds trapped in their shoes.  I've sent previous warnings about these 20 inch thorns on their 20 foot branches falling with no response!, so you don't mind if I leave copies of these few notices with cars or people who I see injured do you?  These are city trees on city property.  If your trimmers want to trim trees all the less then tell them to trim the branches so that they're at an upward angle, and all of the visable seed pods are removed!  From what I've seen in the past they only trim the dead hanging branches while leaving the green hanging branches. - Yes, I agree that that is the best way for the trees to look, but trimming like I'm saying doesn't take long to  soon look totally normal.  I should know, because I used to professionally trim palms many years ago.  So beware, they're not only putting people to the ground, but it looks like they're breaking windows now!

Public Description: -----Original Message-----From: Dick Capen [mailto:rgcapen@aol.com] Sent: Monday, June 13, 2016 11:20 AMTo: Public Utilities Customer Support <Water@sandiego.gov>Subject: West Muirlands Drive Water Pipe ReplacementI want to commend the Burtech Pipeline people who have installed the new water pipes on our street. I have gained great respect for the complexity of this project that was to be completed by May 15, 2016. Unfortunately they have left the project because a connector elbow is needed. Thus, there are several plates at the top of our street with water leaking out.What needs to be done immediately is a clean sweep of the street. The grinding material and dust is heavy along a wide swath of the street. It is tracked onto our driveways and has been causing staining on our concrete driveway for almost three months.Cant someone send a sweeper out to clean up West Muirlands Drive until the installation can be completed. And, when will the street itself be repaved.Sincerely,Ambassador Dick Capen1384 West Muirlands DriveLa Jolla858-354-6712 (cell)

Subject: Pothole  at 4794 35th Street, San Diego, CA, United States
Public Description: City-hired contractors recently completed a sidewalk job on 35th street between Adams Ave and Collier Ave. While the sidewalks look great, the tie-in to the existing asphalt in the roadway fails to meet city standards, so much so that my neighbor, who shares a common driveway with me, cannot pull into his driveway anymore without damaging the bottom of his car. Per the City of San Diego's Street Design Manual, "All streets not superelevated shall be crowned at 2 percent" (p. 115). While I do not have the technical equipment to measure the cross slope at the aforementioned area, the cross-slope is undoubtedly greater than 2 percent. During sidewalk construction, I requested with the contractors to speak to the RE. I was told that the RE was not available and that the issue with the grade break would be resolved in the coming weeks with a full roadway rehabilitation. This discussion took place weeks ago, and I do not see signs of a pavement project. My request is to take measures to bring the street to standard condition, at the very least as close to standard as possible. There is roadway work on-going on the streets nearby, though I do not know if they are AC projects. Perhaps AC work on my street can be added as an addendum item. Best regards,Amanda

Subject: Curb Faded Paint at Cadman Park and Recreation Center, San Diego, CA, United States
Public Description: Cadman Park is an active municipal park with many civic functions scheduled throughout the year with attendant parking issues common to public parkland such as this.  Park users require parking spaces to accommodate their needs when visiting Cadman but parked vehicles often create safety issues for nearby residents as well as for those same park users.  Adequate sight lines need to be reserved to permit safe movement onto adjacent streets, especially during times of heavy Park use.  The enclosed photo shows how I believe street markings can be improved to facilitate the safe movement of vehicles being operated in the vicinity of the Park.1.	Red-painted curbs need to be extended to provide better sight lines at these intersections:a.	Moraga Avenue and Moraga Court ? The red-painted curbs should be extended at least two car lengths [36 additional feet] on the west side of Moraga Avenue both north and south of this intersection.  Drivers attempting to enter Moraga Avenue from Moraga Court are blind to traffic both northbound and southbound on Moraga Avenue.b.	Avati Drive and Wayne Lane ? The red-painted curbs need to be extended at least two car lengths [36 additional feet] on the west side of Avati Drive north of this intersection.  Drivers attempting to enter Avati Drive from Wayne Lane are blind to downhill traffic on Avati Drive. [Not depicted on the accompanying photo]2.	Red-painted curb needs to be painted at the driveway to the ball fields at the curve on Avati Drive.  This driveway is the only access to the ballfields for mowers and other equipment and would be the only access for emergency vehicles if those vehicles required access to the ballfields.  It is routinely blocked by vehicles especially during Little League play at Cadman.3.	Red-painted curb should be extended an additional 36 feet to the first residential driveway on the north side of Moraga Court.  Moraga Court is not wide enough west of the Moraga Avenue/Moraga Court intersection to permit a safe clearance between vehicles parked on Moraga Court and vehicles entering Moraga Court from Moraga Avenue.I believe the curb markings described above will provide a significant additional margin of safety for all of us who live and play in the vicinity of Cadman Park. Your attention to this matter will be greatly appreciated by the thousands of visitors who make Cadman Park their destination for outdoor fun throughout the year.

Public Description: The street is being re-surfaced in my area.  The repair crew said that the problem area @ 4365 & 4361 Argos Dr. has not designated for repair by the City Inspector. I ask that the City inspects the problem for repair prior to applying the slurry so that City money is not being wasted.  Feel free to contact me in person or by phone & please leave a call-back number if I am not available to speak with someone "in person."  Thank you.

Subject: Traffic Signal Signal Facing Wrong Direction at TORREY PINES ROAD & LA JOLLA PARKWAY
Public Description: The light signal is not actually facing the wrong direction.  The issue is that since the installation of the video-based signal timing adjustment system the left turn lane from Torrey Pines Road to LJ Pkwy does not clear all traffic in the lane resulting in backups to Caminito del Cid.  The previously used in-road sensor would efficiently change the light at low volumes of cross traffic and would consistently time to fully clear the left turn lane on each cycle.  Now it barely clears 4 cars at a time if everyone is quick on the accelerator.  The video timing system is supposed to make things better and might even reduce LJ Pkwy backup at the expense of additional traffic on Torrey Pines Rd towards Ardath Lane.Nearly all signals in the area (TP Road East left turn to TP Road North, TP Road split at Caminito del Cid East, TP Road & LJ Pkwy merge at Caminito del Cid West) seem to have shortened resulting in incomplete clearing of accumulated traffic.  The video timing system is supposed to improve things but so far the perceived wait (especially measured in number of cycles to get through an intersection) has increased.

Subject: Traffic Signal Signal Facing Wrong Direction at 5131-5139 College Ave, San Diego, CA 92115, USA
Public Description: There is a tremendous backup of southbound traffic going up the hill on College Ave to SDSU. This is being caused by the (northbound) College Ave. left turn light for Lindo Paseo being on when it shouldn't. First, Lindo Paseo is blocked. So, there's no need for the left turn light to be on. Second, the street has been dug up right where the left turn lane would be. My guess is this is causing the signal to think there is a line of cars turning left when the left signal goes on, because it stays on a LONG time, perhaps 4x longer than the left turn signal that comes on for southbound traffic. So, when that left turn signal for southbound traffic turns red and the northbound traffic starts up to head down the hill, the northbound traffic is still WAITING for the left turn signal to (blocked) Lindo Paseo to turn red so their light can turn green. During those 10+ seconds when their light SHOULD be green, the Montezuma Rd. light is also green, providing the needed flow through the area. This left turn signal for Lindo Paseo , on for an unreasonable amount of time,is keeping that flow from happening, and causing the backup all the way down the hill. Sorry for the above "Type" selectio nof "Signal Facing Wrong Direction". It is a required field and that was the best I could do with the options available. Perhaps "Other" could be considered.

Subject: Traffic Signal All Lights Out at Carmel Valley Rd, San Diego, CA 92130, USA
Public Description: The lights are working at this intersection, but I couldn't find an appropriate Detail choice for "Improper Timing" or "Other"...The traffic signal at Shasta Daisy Trail and Carmel Valley Rd. (92130) appears to have been recently adjusted.  This may be due to the townhome construction project to the east of this intersection.Traffic going through on Carmel Valley Rd. is frequently encountering red lights that last far too long for the cross traffic coming from Shasta Daisy Trail.  Today, at around noon, I sat behind a lineup of cars heading east/west on Carmel Valley Rd. waiting excessively long for the light to turn green while there were simply no cars crossing or entering the intersection from Shasta Daisy Trail.Can this light be adjusted again to give priority to traffic on Carmel Valley Rd.?  The speed limit here is 55mph which is appropriate for this wide road, but the addition of traffic signal lights over the past several years with the ongoing housing and commercial development is making travel along this road very inconvenient.  Better timing of the signals to improve traffic flow and unnecessary waiting would be greatly appreciated.Can the traffic signal at the intersection of Shasta Daisy Trail and Carmel Valley Rd.  please be properly adjusted again to give priority to Carmel Valley Rd. traffic flow?Thanks,Bijan

Subject: Sidewalk  at 12828 Corbett Ct
Public Description: I have a concern about a property on Corbett Ct (92130) and I'm find a way to rectify it.The homeowners at 12828 Corbett Ct have had a portable basketball hoop blocking the sidewalk for a while now, pushing anybody walking past their house into the street.  They're also growing hedges right up to the border of the sidewalk and more often than not, they also have a car or truck parked right up to the curb beside the hoop.  Anybody in a wheelchair or pulling a wagon would have to divert into the middle of the street, and anyone trying to navigate through the obstructions would risk tripping over them.  It's not very neighborly and it's frankly a hazard.I've never seen anyone using the basketball hoop, which would be impossible with the car that's often parked there, but I usually only walk by on weekend mornings.  They're not the only ones who use the public sidewalk for their personal basketball hoop, but it's by far the most difficult and dangerous to navigate.I pointed it out to one of the homeowners as I walked by one morning 2 weeks ago, and I put a note on the hoop last week in an attempt to informally appeal to their sense of reason.  The note is now gone, nothing has changed this week, and again, a car was parked right alongside the hoop this morning.I'm unable to find any specific regulations that speak to leaving portable basketball hoops on the sidewalk, but perhaps you're aware of something.  I'd very much like to see this obstruction removed to make the neighborhood safer and more welcoming to pedestrians.

I saw a lady walking east on Aero Dr. 9700 block & she had to step into the street to get around a large tree branch that was laying across the sidewalk.  The North side of their Ruffin Business Center Sign is maintained, but South of their Sign  3625-3675 Ruffin Business Center has not been touched in years & is really dangerous to walkers, bikers & cars.

Public Description: The sidewalk in front of our house continues to lift more and more creating a tripping hazard as people leave our home. We've had 3 people trip and hurt themselves.  This is a result of the parkway tree causing the sidewalk to be lifted 3" as people exit our front walk onto the sidewalk.  My mother is a disabled senior with a bad back and she tripped leaving our home. One of our child's teenage friends also tripped while leaving the home.  You have been out to review the situation previously and the city workers acknowledged that it is a big hazard; they indicated that they were referring to the street division who would remove the parkway tree and repair the sidewalk.   They acknowledged that this is city property and nothing we as homeowners can do to remedy. Then, suddenly, the ticket was closed.  The problem is continuing to become worse with the roots causing a tripping hazard as people exit their cars from the curb as well as the sidewalk is lifted between slabs.
